    <p><strong>Knivskjellodden</strong> is a peninsula on the island of Magerøya extending to latitude <strong>71°11′08″N</strong> — approximately 1,457 metres further north than the Nordkapp plateau (71°10′21″N), making it the actual northernmost point of mainland Europe. The Nordkapp plateau is more accessible by road and more widely marketed, but Knivskjellodden is the geographic record-holder. The land is publicly accessible under Norway's freedom-to-roam laws. There is no fee, no permit, and no ticket required.</p>
    <p>The marked trail begins at a car park on the <strong>E69 highway, approximately 7 km before the Nordkapp plateau</strong>. The trail is approximately 9 km one way (18 km round trip) across open Arctic tundra — flat but exposed, with no shelter at any point. Typical round-trip time is 4–6 hours. The terrain is not technically difficult but weather conditions can change rapidly; full waterproof and windproof clothing, warm layers, sturdy footwear, food, water, and navigation equipment are required regardless of the season.</p>
    <p>The E69 is open to all traffic continuously in summer. In winter, access to Magerøya via the E69 is by scheduled convoy departing from Honningsvåg — hikers travelling independently must time their journey to arrive with the convoy. Check road status at vegvesen.no and weather at yr.no before departing. Trail information is available at ut.no. Last updated: March 2026 · Verified</p>
