    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">Is Knivskjellodden free to visit?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">Yes. Knivskjellodden is open public land under Norway's freedom-to-roam laws. There is no entrance fee, no gate, and no ticket required. The trail starts from a free car park on the E69, approximately 7 km before the Nordkapp plateau. Any website selling a "ticket" to Knivskjellodden is fraudulent.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">How long is the hike to Knivskjellodden?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">The marked trail is approximately 9 km one way — 18 km round trip. Total hiking time is typically 4–6 hours round trip. The terrain is open Arctic tundra, flat but fully exposed with no shelter. The trail starts from the car park on the E69, approximately 7 km before the Nordkapp plateau.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">Is Knivskjellodden further north than Nordkapp?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">Yes. Knivskjellodden extends approximately 1,457 metres further north than the Nordkapp plateau, reaching latitude 71°11′08″N versus Nordkapp's 71°10′21″N. Nordkapp is accessible by road with the Nordkapphallen visitor centre; Knivskjellodden is the actual northernmost point and requires the 18km round-trip hike.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">When can you hike to Knivskjellodden?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">The trail is accessible when the E69 is open. In summer (May–October) the road is open to all traffic continuously. In winter, the E69 operates under a convoy system from Honningsvåg — independent hikers must join the convoy. Arctic weather can change rapidly at any time of year. Check road status at vegvesen.no and weather at yr.no before departing.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">What equipment is needed for the Knivskjellodden hike?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">Required equipment: waterproof and windproof outer layers, warm insulating layers, sturdy footwear, map or GPS, water, food, and a charged phone. The terrain is open tundra with no shelter at any point. Check yr.no for weather before departing. In summer, 24-hour daylight means visibility is not a limiting factor, but cold wind and fog can develop rapidly.</div>
    </div>
